@node WhatIsMotoWB "What is MotoWB?"

  What is MotoWB?
  ---------------

  In short: Motorola logos in three versions for use with MagicWB-compliant
            Commodore-Amiga workstations.

  MotoWB is my contribution to the steadily growing library of background
  pictures for the Workbench screen and windows. It is designed for use
  with the new MagicWB v2 palette (8 colors minimum), and will most
  certainly not look good with any other palette. Likewise, the large
  pictures will only work OK in 640x512 or something similar, preferably
  DblPal HiRes No Flicker (which I'm using), or possibly Multiscan
  Productivity (640x480).

  You could of course always edit the pictures yourself to center/resize the
  images. The 'Images/' drawer contains the mask for the large image. Thus,
  you can trace it to vectors and scale it, or do whatever you like with it.
  - Why not first trace and then ray trace...


@endnode


@node Installation

  Installation
  ------------

  Assuming you have a copy of the Commodore Installer lying around somewhere:

  Just start the installation script named 'MotoWB-Install' from the
  Workbench. The script will ask you where to place the pictures, default
  is 'SYS:Prefs/Patterns'. Only the contents of the 'Pictures' drawer
  will be copied.

  You can also do the copying yourself if you don't have the installer, by
  writing the following command in a shell window (assuming that the
  directory in which this AmigaGuide file resides is the current directory):

    copy Pictures/~(#?.info) SYS:Prefs/Patterns

  [This will also create the directory if it doesn't already exist.]

  Note: Old users of MotoWB will need to temporarily select another
        background for the Workbench while installing the new files. This is
        because Workbench puts a lock on the file, and the installer will
        abort with an error, saying that the file is already in use.

@endnode


@node AboutTheAuthor "About the Author"

  About the Author
  ----------------

  My name is Kristofer Maad, and I'm studying mathematics and computer
  science at the Uppsala University in Sweden. I am really more of a
  programmer than an artist, but I felt that I needed to let my feelings for
  our beloved CPU out in a sensitive, yet powerful and convincing experience
  to eye and mind... er... not. Anyway, it's better than the ugly grey screen,
  don't you think?

  If you would like to contact me, for whatever reason, see the @{"Copyright" Link Copyright}
  section.

@endnode

